  "answer": "Manu Book 1 makes varna cosmogonic in the strictest sense: the four social orders emanate directly from the body of the creator during the act of world-making. The representative passage is Mn_1.31 (p-13a2db): 'And for the sake of the prosperity of the worlds, he caused the Brahmana, the Kshatriya, the Vaishya, and the Shudra to emanate from his mouth, arms, thighs, and feet.' This is reinforced by Mn_1.87 (p-f0b26c), where the creator 'assigned separate duties to those born from his mouth, arms, thighs, and feet.' The varnas are not social inventions or historical arrangements — they are written into the structure of existence before history begins. Hierarchy is cosmic necessity.\n\nSlokantara (unknown-slokantara-d7a628, ch.1) uses the same varna vocabulary and even echoes the cosmogonic idiom: Slo_28 (p-605381) calls the Śūdra 'those born from the feet.' But the operative logic is entirely different. The defining passage is Slo_25 (p-0f2d04): 'For the special qualities of a person, birth is certainly not the measure.' The Kawi commentary makes this concrete: honey comes from stinging-nettle flowers, milk from buffalo blood, the lotus from mud — virtue has nothing to do with origin. Slo_26 (p-d928ee) presses further: knowledge should be received even from a lowly person, and a jewel of a woman taken from any family.\n\nWhere Slokantara does define varna roles — Vaishya as farmers and cattle-herders (Slo_27, p-428c5c), Śūdra as sea-traders doing commerce (Slo_28, p-605381) — the definitions are entirely occupational. Status is also losable: Slo_30 (p-5a8fb0) says that a Brahmin who abandons ancestral duties and lives by others' work is reclassified with the Caṇḍālas. Social position is thus performative and behavioral, not ontological.\n\nThe conclusion: Slokantara does not presuppose Manu's cosmogonic framework. It borrows Manu's taxonomy and occasionally his idioms (including the 'born from the feet' formula) as received cultural vocabulary, but its grounding logic is pragmatic rather than cosmogonic. Where Manu justifies hierarchy by cosmic necessity — you are a Brahmin because the creator's mouth shaped you — Slokantara's Kawi gnomic register recasts varna as a code of expected conduct: you are a Brahmin if you practice celibacy, master the Vedas, and avoid impurity, and you lose that identity if you defect from those duties. Birth is explicitly said not to be the measure. The two texts share a vocabulary while operating within different metaphysical frameworks.",
